      "title": "Social Cohesion in Post-Conflict and Divided Societies: Recent Advances",
      "abstract": "Although the study of social cohesion in divided and post-conflict societies has grown within social psychology, addressing social cohesion remains complex because it is multidimensional and multilevel. This special issue introduction advances understanding of the dynamics of social cohesion across contexts marked by deep social divisions and intergroup tensions, where achieving cohesion is particularly challenging. It showcases research examining different dimensions of social cohesion and explores how such analyses can inform efforts to foster cohesion and improve intra- and intergroup relations. Bringing together empirical articles using quantitative and qualitative methods in diverse divided and post-conflict contexts, the article highlights how identities, narratives, trust, belonging, participation, and institutional arrangements shape social cohesion.",
